Advanced Regression Assignment

Author: Anish Mahapatra

Machine Learning II > Module 3

Problem Statement

US-based housing company Suprise Housing would like to enter the Australian Market. The company uses data analytics to purchase houses at a price below their actual values and flip them on at a higher price. For the same purpose, the company has collected a data set from the sale of houses in Australia.

The company is looking at prospective properties to buy to enter the market. A regression model using regularisation is to be built in order to predict the actual value of the prospective properties and decide whether to invest in them or not.

The company wants to know the following:

  • Which variables are significant in predicting the price of a house, and
  • How well those variables describe the price of a house.

We are also to determine the optimal value of lambda for ridge and lasso regression.

Goals of case Study:

The price of the house is to be modelled with the available independent variables. The model will be used by the management to understand how the prices vary with the variables. Based on this input, the strategy of the firm can be manipulated to yield high returns. The model will also enable the management to understand the pricing dynamics of the new market

Evaluation Rubric:

  • Data Quality Checks - missing value imputation, removing duplicate data, data redundancies
  • Data Quality Issues mentioned and clearly explained in comments
  • Dummy variables are created & New Metrics are derived, wherever applicable
  • Model Parameters are tuned using correct principles (Both Technical and Business)
  • Correct Variable Selection Techniques are used, reasonable number of models are iterated over
  • Model evaluation using correct principles and appropriate evaluation metrics are chosen
  • Model is interpreted and explained correctly

Data Cleaning

  • Handle actual missing values
  • Find percentage of missing values
  • Drop columns that have a high percentage of missing values
  • Drop columns that are highly skewed
  • Impute data wherever required
  • Check if target variable (Sales price) is normally distributed or not. If it is not normally distributed, perform transformation to make it normally distributed
  • Create dummy variables from categorical columns
  • Convert year column to find age by using Age = max(YearColumn) - year in the row
  • Scale the data

Modeling

  • Perform Ridge and Lasso Regression
  • Perform Hyperparameter tuning to get optimal lambda
  • Describe the model

We realize that a lot of the columns have 'NA' values. There are two kinds of missing values here:

  1. Actual missing values in the form of NA - indicative of missing entries
  2. Meaningful NA values that are indicative of a missing feature

Type I: Actual Missing Values

  • LotFrontage: Linear feet of street connected to property
  • MasVnrType: Masonry veneer type - This attribute has type None to indicate that the feature is missing. Hence, NA is indicative of atual missing value
  • MasVnrArea: Masonry veneer area in square feet
  • Electrical: Electrical system - NA indicative of actual missing data

Type II: Indicative of the feature missing on the property

  • Alley: Type of alley access to property
  • BsmtQual: Evaluates the height of the basement
  • BsmtCond: Evaluates the general condition of the basement
  • BsmtExposure: Refers to walkout or garden level walls
  • BsmtFinType1: Rating of basement finished area
  • BsmtFinType2: Rating of basement finished area (if multiple types)
  • FireplaceQu: Fireplace quality
  • GarageType: Garage location
  • GarageYrBlt: Year garage was built
  • GarageFinish: Interior finish of the garage
  • GarageQual: Garage quality
  • GarageCond: Garage condition
  • PoolQC: Pool quality
  • Fence: Fence quality
  • MiscFeature: Miscellaneous feature not covered in other categories

Handling Missing values

In [10]:
# Replacing 'NA' values with missing values for the columns that have actual missing values

df['LotFrontage'] = df['LotFrontage'].replace('NA','')
df['MasVnrType'] = df['MasVnrType'].replace('NA','')
df['MasVnrArea'] = df['MasVnrArea'].replace('NA','')
df['Electrical'] = df['Electrical'].replace('NA','')
df['GarageYrBlt'] = df['GarageYrBlt'].replace('NA','')
In [11]:
# Replacing the 'NA' values with what they are indicative of instead of missing values
df['Alley'].fillna('NoAlley', inplace = True) 
df['BsmtQual'].fillna('NoBasement', inplace = True) 
df['BsmtCond'].fillna('NoBasement', inplace = True) 
df['BsmtExposure'].fillna('NoBasement', inplace = True) 
df['BsmtFinType1'].fillna('NoBasement', inplace = True) 
df['BsmtFinType2'].fillna('NoBasement', inplace = True) 
df['FireplaceQu'].fillna('NoFireplace', inplace = True) 
df['GarageType'].fillna('NoGarage', inplace = True) 
df['GarageFinish'].fillna('NoGarage', inplace = True) 
df['GarageQual'].fillna('NoGarage', inplace = True) 
df['GarageCond'].fillna('NoGarage', inplace = True) 
df['PoolQC'].fillna('NoPool', inplace = True) 
df['Fence'].fillna('NoFence', inplace = True) 
df['MiscFeature'].fillna('NoMiscFeature', inplace = True)

Mapping and dummy one-hot encoding

Column that has binary mapping:

  • CentralAir

Rest of the categorical columns would require dummy one-hot encoding.

Binary Encoding

In [14]:
# List of variables to map
variableList =  ['CentralAir']

# Defining the map function
def binary_map(x):
    return x.map({'Y': 1, 'N': 0})

# Applying the function to the housing list
df[variableList] = df[variableList].apply(binary_map)

Feature Engineering on the Year Columns

We shall now convert the year columns: GarageYrBlt, YrSold, YearBuilt & YearRemodAdd to the number of years.

The logic we shall use is

  • Number of Years = Current Year (2020) - Row Value<\b>

We also not that the % of missing values in the above-mentioned columns is NIL.

In [23]:
df.shape
Out[23]:
(1460, 81)
In [24]:
df = df_dummy.copy(deep = True)
In [25]:
def numberOfYears(df, colName):
    '''
    Function to replace the year columns with the number of years
    '''
    maxValue = df[colName].max()
    modDf = df[colName].apply(lambda x: maxValue - x)
    return modDf
In [26]:
df['GarageYrBlt'] = numberOfYears(df, 'GarageYrBlt')
df['YrSold'] = numberOfYears(df, 'YrSold')
df['YearBuilt'] = numberOfYears(df, 'YearBuilt')
df['YearRemodAdd'] = numberOfYears(df, 'YearRemodAdd')

Analysis of feature to be predicted

Let us view the histogram of the SalePrice column to understand the distribution of the feature to be predicted.

In [29]:
# Viewing the histogram of the feature
df['SalePrice'].hist(bins=100, figsize=[14,6])
Out[29]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x2951e8ada48>

Here, we notice that the distribution is skewed. We shall apply a transformation to the variable to make the distribution normal.

Log Transformation of Predicted variable - SalePrice

In [30]:
# Log Transofrmation of SalePrice 
df['SalePrice'] = np.log(df.SalePrice)
In [31]:
# Viewing the histogram of the feature
df['SalePrice'].hist(bins=100, figsize=[14,6])
Out[31]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x29520fe7c08>

We notice that after we apply LOG transformation, the dataset has a normal distribution now.
